article.headline: Arkansas State 78, Arkansas LR 66
article.story: JONESBORO, Ark. (AP) -- The Arkansas-Little Rock Trojans can be forgiven if they don't want to see Dereke Tipler again. The Arkansas State senior guard led the Indians with 22 points in a 78-66 victory over UALR Saturday afternoon. Earlier this month, Tipler scored a career-high 30 points -- 24 in the second half -- as ASU topped the Trojans 74-70. "He's a warrior," UALR coach Steve Shields said. "He really is. He is a tough-minded young man. He did a great job." It was actually the third time in the last four games Tipler has hurt the Trojans. In ASU's 78-64 victory over UALR last year, Tipler kept the Trojans' top scorer, Brandon Freeman, from making a single field goal. "Dereke loves rivalries and he gets riled up for big games," ASU coach Dickie Nutt said. It was the third victory in four games for the Indians (9-13, 4-4 SBC) against their cross-state rival UALR (11-8, 4-3). Tipler was 8-of-10 from the foul line and also had seven assists, grabbed five rebounds and made four steals. Aside from Tipler, both teams mounted balanced scoring attacks. For ASU, Marcus Ardison scored 14, Yual Banks -- perfect on five shots -- added 13 points and Jim Jones scored 12. ASU used only seven players in the game. "Yual really came up big," Nutt said. "He is developing into a nice shooting guard." UALR was led by Zack Wright with 14 points, while Elijah Muldrow added 13 points, Rashad Jones-Jennings scored 11 and Byron Ray had 10. The Indians led 41-30 at intermission after shooting 61 percent in the first half. In the second half, UALR got as close as three points on three occasions, the last time at 62-59 with 3:28 left, but Banks hit a 3-pointer 20 seconds later. "You have to give credit to Arkansas State. We fought back and did a good job in the second half and got as close as three," Shields said. "Banks' 3-pointer was a big shot." Zack Wright's free throw trimmed the margin to 65-60, but ASU answered with an Ardison jumper and Tipler's driving full-court layup and free throw for a 70-60 lead with 1:27 to play. UALR, which had a 34-26 rebound advantage, made only 38 percent of their field-goal attempts, while ASU finished at 59 percent.
